      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Hormones and the Menstrual Cycle</h5>

          <p>
            The menstrual cycle is regulated by a complex interplay of hormones
            that prepare the body for pregnancy each month.
          </p>

          <h6 class="mt-3">Key Hormones</h6>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Estrogen</strong> - Primarily produced by the ovaries;
              responsible for developing and maintaining female sexual
              characteristics and reproductive system
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Progesterone</strong> - Produced mainly by the corpus
              luteum after ovulation; prepares the uterine lining for
              implantation
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Follicle-Stimulating Hormone (FSH)</strong> - Produced by
              the pituitary gland; stimulates the growth of ovarian follicles
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Luteinizing Hormone (LH)</strong> - Produced by the
              pituitary gland; triggers ovulation
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h6 class="mt-3">Hormonal Changes Throughout Life</h6>
          <div class="table-responsive">
            <table class="table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Life Stage</th>
                  <th>Hormonal Changes</th>
                  <th>Effects</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td>Puberty</td>
                  <td>Rising estrogen and progesterone</td>
                  <td>
                    Development of breasts, pubic hair, body fat changes,
                    beginning of menstruation
                  </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Reproductive Years</td>
                  <td>Cyclical changes in hormones</td>
                  <td>Regular menstrual cycles, fertility</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Perimenopause</td>
                  <td>Fluctuating hormones, declining estrogen</td>
                  <td>Irregular periods, hot flashes, mood changes</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Menopause</td>
                  <td>Significantly reduced estrogen and progesterone</td>
                  <td>
                    End of menstruation, changes in bone density, skin, and
                    vaginal tissue
                  </td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Sexual Health</h5>

          <p>
            Sexual health is an essential part of overall wellbeing and
            encompasses physical, emotional, mental, and social aspects of
            sexuality.
          </p>

          <h6 class="mt-3">Maintaining Sexual Health</h6>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Regular Gynecological Exams</strong> - Important for early
              detection of issues and preventive care
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Safe Sex Practices</strong> - Using barriers (condoms,
              dental dams) to reduce STI risk
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Open Communication</strong> - Discussing boundaries,
              desires, and concerns with partners
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Regular STI Testing</strong> - Important part of
              responsible sexual health
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Understanding Consent</strong> - Ensuring all sexual
              activity is wanted and consensual
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h6 class="mt-3">Common Sexual Health Concerns</h6>
          <div class="accordion" id="sexualHealthAccordion">
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingLibido">
                <button
                  class="accordion-button collapsed"
