          <h5 class="card-title">Sexual Health Myths vs. Facts</h5>

          <div class="myth-fact mb-3">
            <p class="fw-bold text-danger">
              Myth: You can't get pregnant during your period.
            </p>
            <p class="fw-bold text-success">
              Fact: While less likely, pregnancy can occur if you have sex
              during your period, especially if you have a shorter cycle or
              irregular periods.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="myth-fact mb-3">
            <p class="fw-bold text-danger">
              Myth: Birth control pills cause weight gain.
            </p>
            <p class="fw-bold text-success">
              Fact: Research suggests that most modern birth control pills don't
              cause significant weight gain. Individual responses vary, and some
              may experience water retention.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="myth-fact mb-3">
            <p class="fw-bold text-danger">
              Myth: You can't get an STI from oral sex.
            </p>
            <p class="fw-bold text-success">
              Fact: Several STIs, including herpes, gonorrhea, and syphilis, can
              be transmitted through oral sex.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="myth-fact mb-3">
            <p class="fw-bold text-danger">
              Myth: Douching helps keep the vagina clean and healthy.
            </p>
            <p class="fw-bold text-success">
              Fact: Douching can disrupt the natural balance of bacteria in the
              vagina, potentially leading to infections. The vagina is
              self-cleaning.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="myth-fact">
            <p class="fw-bold text-danger">
              Myth: Pap smears test for all STIs.
            </p>
            <p class="fw-bold text-success">
              Fact: Pap smears screen primarily for cervical cancer and HPV.
              Specific STI tests must be requested separately.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

